            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
                <p>ΛΗΝΑΙΟΣ is most likely a personal name. It is followed by an probable alpha (or a lambda with an accidental horizontal stroke that extends 
                    far to the left beyond lambda's left diagonal) and quite a clear circle, which should presumably be read 
                    as an omicron, so I read ΑΟ. <!--I cannot see the proposed reading (by whom?) ΠΙΝΩ?  --> The circle that follows alpha does not have legs and 
                    therefore cannot be an omega, unless we are dealing with Attic script, which is not likely here.
                    There might be a letter (diamond-shaped?) between the iota and omicron of ΛΗΝΑΙΟΣ, unless the strokes are accidental. 
                 In fact, the whole graffito is very messy: there are many double strokes and slips of the writing tool. The surface, while convex, 
                 was not so difficult for writing, and the writer had to be either inexperienced or with their hand unsteadied (by drink?). 
                 Lenaios is a personal name that comes from the month Lenaion. It was an Ionian, not an Attic month, and was specifically a Milesian and Olbian month, so we should perhaps lean towards expecting the 
                    writer to be Ionian and using the Ionian alphabet. Seven more individuals bearingthis name are attested at Olbia-Borysthenes (e.g. LGPN V4-19517).
                    <!--Tolstoy 1953, no. 75; IGDOlbia no. 70; SEG 30.883 -->
                    <!--Tolstoy no. 75. Rusyaeva 1979, 80-81 discusses the name and the month.--></p>
            </div>
